'''Bidau Creole Portuguese''' (''Português de Bidau'') was a [[Portuguese Creole|Portuguese-based creole language]] that was spoken in [[Bidau]], an eastern suburb of [[Dili]], [[East Timor]] until the 1960s, when the speakers shifted to standard [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]].{{citation needed|date=October 2018}}

Bidau Creole Portuguese grew out of the Portuguese spoken by settlers and ''[[Mestizo|Mestiços]]'' from [[Flores|Flores Island]], influenced by languages introduced to the area by [[military]] men from [[Lifau]]. It shares a number of features with nearby creoles such as [[Macanese language|Macanese]].

