{{Infobox language |name=Lufu |states=[[Nigeria]] |region=[[Taraba State]] |speakers=3,200 |date=2006 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4= [[Plateau languages|Plateau]] |fam5= [[Yukubenic languages|Yukubenic]] |fam6= Bete–Lufu |iso3=ldq |glotto=lufu1237 |glottorefname=Lufu }}
The '''Lufu language''' is a [[Yukubenic]] language of [[Nigeria]] is a language still spoken mostly by older adults among the Lufu people of the [[Takum|Takum Local Government Authority]], [[Taraba State]]; its speakers have mostly shifted to [[Jukun Takum language|Jukun]]. It is close to [[Bete language (Nigeria)|Bete]].
==Bibliography== * Crozier, David H. and [[Roger M. Blench]], editors. 1992. ''An index of Nigerian languages''. Abuja, Nigeria and Dallas: Nigerian Language Development Centre, Department of Linguistics and Nigerian Languages, University of Ilorin, and [[Summer Institute of Linguistics]].
